### What problem does this feature solve?
When I read the source code, I found that function  `normalizeProps` and `normalizeInject` similar, but not the same writing.

The file path: `vue/src/core/util/options.js`

```js
function normalizeProps (options, vm) {
    var props = options.props;
    if (!props) { return }
    var res = {};
    ...
          res[name] = { type: null };
    ...
        res[name] = isPlainObject(val)
          ? val
          : { type: val };
   ...
    options.props = res;
  }
```

```js
function normalizeInject (options, vm) {
    var inject = options.inject;
    if (!inject) { return }
    var normalized = options.inject = {};
    ...
        normalized[inject[i]] = { from: inject[i] };
    ...
        normalized[key] = isPlainObject(val)
          ? extend({ from: key }, val)
          : { from: val };
  }
```

Temporary variables( `res` and `normalized`) are used, Why not use the same writing method?


### What does the proposed API look like?
I prefer the way `normalizeInject` is written. I hope `var res = {}; options.props = res; ` in `normalizeProps` could rewrite link ` var res = options.props = {};`.

This is a small problem, but I think it will make it less confusing for beginners to read the source code

